<article class="article-body">

<p>Most founders hire a Chief of Staff either too early (and bore them) or too late (after months of avoidable chaos). Here are five concrete signs you've actually reached the point where a Chief of Staff pays for itself — and what to do if you're not there yet.</p>

<h2>1. Decisions get made in meetings, then vanish</h2>
<p>If your leadership team agrees on things that never happen — because nobody captured the decision, named an owner, or chased it — that's the single clearest CoS signal. A Chief of Staff turns meetings into tracked commitments.</p>

<h2>2. Strategic projects stall between departments</h2>
<p>Market entry, a systems migration, a partnership — initiatives that touch multiple teams and quietly drift for months because no single person owns the cross-functional execution. A CoS owns exactly that.</p>

<h2>3. You're the bottleneck on everything cross-team</h2>
<p>If every decision that spans two departments routes through you, you've become the integration layer. A Chief of Staff absorbs that load so the company moves without you in the middle of it.</p>

<h2>4. Board prep is a recurring panic</h2>
<p>Assembling the board pack the night before, every quarter, is a sign the operating rhythm is missing. A CoS runs board and investor operations on a calendar, not in a scramble.</p>

<h2>5. Your leadership team has outgrown its rhythm</h2>
<p>Once you have four or more people in leadership, informal coordination breaks down. The cadence — weekly meetings, OKR check-ins, decision logs — becomes its own job.</p>

<h2>If you only see one or two signs</h2>
<p>You probably don't need a full Chief of Staff yet. If the pain is your calendar and inbox, hire an <a href="/executive-assistant-kenya/">executive assistant</a>. If it's team reliability and systems, that's an <a href="/operations-manager-kenya/">operations manager</a>. If it's a bit of everything and you're not ready for multiple hires, one senior <a href="/operations-partner/">operations partner</a> covers the blend. The role differences are mapped in <a href="/blog/chief-of-staff-vs-executive-assistant/">Chief of Staff vs Executive Assistant</a>.</p>

<h2>The fractional shortcut</h2>
<p>Seeing three or more signs but not ready for a $200K+ full-time executive? That's exactly what a <a href="/fractional-chief-of-staff/">fractional Chief of Staff</a> is for — the operating system, part-time, on monthly terms.</p>

